00:16:43.759 --> 00:16:48.480
that we want and they are optimal for

00:16:45.920 --> 00:16:51.920
that task. We don't want to go learn the

00:16:48.480 --> 00:16:57.440
domain of computer vision and all of

00:16:51.920 --> 00:17:00.880
these kernels and then uh develop u um

00:16:57.440 --> 00:17:03.440
skill on how to make this tradeoffs and

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:05.839
make this decisions to basically use

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:08.240
this dictionary of fixed kernel. And

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:11.199
instead we want deep learning to do all

00:17:08.240 --> 00:17:14.559
of that for us. learn the kernels and

00:17:11.199 --> 00:17:16.959
these kernels are actually optimized for

00:17:14.559 --> 00:17:20.880
the specific task that we have.

00:17:16.959 --> 00:17:24.079
Crossorrelation or sweeping uh function

00:17:20.880 --> 00:17:26.480
that learns this features in each one of

00:17:24.079 --> 00:17:28.559
these patches of the window has a nice

00:17:26.480 --> 00:17:31.200
property that is called translation

00:17:28.559 --> 00:17:34.320
equivalence. If you shift the input, for

00:17:31.200 --> 00:17:36.960
example, if you have a image of a cat

00:17:34.320 --> 00:17:40.160
here, if you move this to somewhere else

00:17:36.960 --> 00:17:43.679
in the image, it's the same thing. And

00:17:40.160 --> 00:17:46.160
we want the neural network to uh not use

00:17:43.679 --> 00:17:48.799
uh extra learning

00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:51.840
capacity for that. In other word, we

00:17:48.799 --> 00:17:56.559
have the same neural network that learns

00:17:51.840 --> 00:17:59.760
this kernel works here and here. And

00:17:56.559 --> 00:18:02.559
that uh sharing of weights across all of

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:06.400
this position give us a parameter

00:18:02.559 --> 00:18:10.080
efficiency that later help us in such

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:13.200
high dimensional space because we really

00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:16.880
reduce the dimension significantly by

00:18:13.200 --> 00:18:20.320
doing this. So then uh next we will talk

00:18:16.880 --> 00:18:22.000
about how we can build such uh neural

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:25.280
network that we are going to call

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:28.880
convolutional neural network. So before

00:18:25.280 --> 00:18:31.840
applying this concepts uh to build our

00:18:28.880 --> 00:18:36.000
first convolutional neural network

00:18:31.840 --> 00:18:39.840
uh let's um review a couple of things.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:43.039
First how we are using this kernel on

00:18:39.840 --> 00:18:46.160
this image data and things that we

00:18:43.039 --> 00:18:48.080
should consider in the implementation.

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:51.120
So for example here this is an image

00:18:48.080 --> 00:18:56.960
from the book. If we have a kernel like

00:18:51.120 --> 00:18:59.600
this and an image u here a 3x3 image or

00:18:56.960 --> 00:19:02.720
maybe a patch but let's assume the image

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:05.200
is like this and now we want to do the

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:08.240
convolution or the cross correlation

00:19:05.200 --> 00:19:12.400
operation using this kernel. So here we

00:19:08.240 --> 00:19:15.039
have this 2x2 kernel and we are going to

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:16.960
start from this part of the image. we do

00:19:15.039 --> 00:19:21.039
the elementwise

00:19:16.960 --> 00:19:24.320
uh crossorrelation operation and this

00:19:21.039 --> 00:19:26.880
will give us the first output here which

00:19:24.320 --> 00:19:29.919
will be 19. If we continue doing this

00:19:26.880 --> 00:19:34.320
for the next part of the image we'll get

00:19:29.919 --> 00:19:37.520
25 and so on and so forth. So we will

00:19:34.320 --> 00:19:40.000
see the output of this operation

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:43.200
here will be a 2x2

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:47.760
uh output which is smaller uh in

00:19:43.200 --> 00:19:51.600
dimension than the the original input

00:19:47.760 --> 00:19:53.360
and if we continue doing this uh steps

00:19:51.600 --> 00:19:56.000
we will

00:19:53.360 --> 00:19:59.760
end up in the next step with only one

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:02.799
out output. So what is the problem here

00:19:59.760 --> 00:20:05.360
is uh sometimes we need more layers in

00:20:02.799 --> 00:20:09.360
our operation in our convolutional

00:20:05.360 --> 00:20:12.400
neural network and this operation will

00:20:09.360 --> 00:20:15.520
reduce the size of uh the dimension of

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:19.360
the the data.

00:20:15.520 --> 00:20:25.760
So to fix this uh very simple trick is

00:20:19.360 --> 00:20:29.840
to pad the uh the data with this

00:20:25.760 --> 00:20:36.480
zeros here. And basically what it does

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:39.200
is to in this case of 2x two we can now

00:20:36.480 --> 00:20:42.559
uh have a output uh corresponding to

00:20:39.200 --> 00:20:45.440
this edge cases on the periphery of the

00:20:42.559 --> 00:20:47.679
the image. And this way we will retain

00:20:45.440 --> 00:20:50.559
the same dimension

00:20:47.679 --> 00:20:54.400
in the output. So keeping aside this

00:20:50.559 --> 00:20:56.320
problem of u reduction of uh dimension

00:20:54.400 --> 00:20:59.200
using padding

00:20:56.320 --> 00:21:02.159
sometimes we actually want to reduce the

00:20:59.200 --> 00:21:04.320
the dimension.

00:21:02.159 --> 00:21:06.000
And if we want to do it we will use

00:21:04.320 --> 00:21:09.200
strides

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:12.480
but basically stride is uh the number of

00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:14.799
rows and columns that we traverse per

00:21:12.480 --> 00:21:19.200
slide.

00:21:14.799 --> 00:21:22.559
So so far uh we used the strides of one

00:21:19.200 --> 00:21:26.640
but we can change that and uh we can

00:21:22.559 --> 00:21:30.559
also change it for heights and weights.

00:21:26.640 --> 00:21:34.000
So for example here this is figure 7 33

00:21:30.559 --> 00:21:37.440
in the book. If we do the stride of uh

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:39.440
three for height and two for the widths.

00:21:37.440 --> 00:21:43.039
For example, in the first one we have

00:21:39.440 --> 00:21:48.240
this and the component wise we will get

00:21:43.039 --> 00:21:51.360
that. But next uh stride will be two in

00:21:48.240 --> 00:21:55.200
the whites. So we have this multiply by

00:21:51.360 --> 00:22:00.159
this and we will get that. And the for

00:21:55.200 --> 00:22:03.200
the height we go uh three we slide this

00:22:00.159 --> 00:22:05.679
uh three times and we will get this

00:22:03.200 --> 00:22:08.960
which multiply by the kernel will give

00:22:05.679 --> 00:22:11.679
us six. And of course for the other

00:22:08.960 --> 00:22:13.679
component if you do it you will get

00:22:11.679 --> 00:22:16.559
eight.

00:22:13.679 --> 00:22:20.640
So this way we can reduce the the

00:22:16.559 --> 00:22:22.960
dimension uh if we desire and while we

00:22:20.640 --> 00:22:25.440
are controlling for it. The next

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:28.000
component that we will use in

00:22:25.440 --> 00:22:30.559
constructing our CNN's

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:34.640
are is uh pooling. Basically pooling

00:22:30.559 --> 00:22:37.760
means that we ask a question from the

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:41.200
learned features and this question is a

00:22:37.760 --> 00:22:43.440
global question meaning that does it

00:22:41.200 --> 00:22:46.400
does this image contain a certain

00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:49.520
feature or a certain object.

00:22:46.400 --> 00:22:52.880
We want this question to be sensitive to

00:22:49.520 --> 00:22:57.600
the entire input.

00:22:52.880 --> 00:23:01.919
So we need to aggregate u this local

00:22:57.600 --> 00:23:05.360
information gradually and uh this way we

00:23:01.919 --> 00:23:07.840
can get coarser and coarser maps and

00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:09.440
ultimately learning a global

00:23:07.840 --> 00:23:11.840
representation.

00:23:09.440 --> 00:23:14.320
So we want to do this in a way that we

00:23:11.840 --> 00:23:18.000
keep all of these advantages that we

00:23:14.320 --> 00:23:20.640
collect in these intermediate layers and

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:24.559
while we are going deeper in the network

00:23:20.640 --> 00:23:27.919
we see more and more uh of this local

00:23:24.559 --> 00:23:30.559
localities and our receptive field

00:23:27.919 --> 00:23:34.559
relative to this initial input will

00:23:30.559 --> 00:23:36.640
increase. So and also if you remember we

00:23:34.559 --> 00:23:39.600
wanted our representation to be

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:41.679
invariant to translation

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:45.200
and so far what we did with the cross

00:23:41.679 --> 00:23:48.720
correlation uh was pretty local. We were

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:50.799
sliding that window and we performed

00:23:48.720 --> 00:23:54.320
cross cororrelation

00:23:50.799 --> 00:23:57.440
uh during each one of these strides. And

00:23:54.320 --> 00:24:00.720
now we want to come up with a another

00:23:57.440 --> 00:24:03.679
step that uh basically inject this

00:24:00.720 --> 00:24:05.600
invariance to translation and pooling is

00:24:03.679 --> 00:24:08.720
doing that for us.

00:24:05.600 --> 00:24:13.760
We have two ways of doing uh this

00:24:08.720 --> 00:24:18.000
process this pooling step step uh I mean

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:19.679
most uh common way of pooling one is max

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:22.240
pooling and the other one is average

00:24:19.679 --> 00:24:25.600
pooling and max pooling basically what

00:24:22.240 --> 00:24:28.640
it does is uh it finds the strongest

00:24:25.600 --> 00:24:32.320
clue and the intuition is basically each

00:24:28.640 --> 00:24:34.799
one of these uh smaller uh

00:24:32.320 --> 00:24:37.760
crossorrelation steps that we are doing

00:24:34.799 --> 00:24:42.000
is like a detective that is zooming in

00:24:37.760 --> 00:24:45.039
into this smaller patches and then after

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:48.159
aggregating all of them it returns the

00:24:45.039 --> 00:24:50.400
strongest evidence that it finds. That's

00:24:48.159 --> 00:24:52.559
max pooling. Another way of doing this

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:54.960
is doing average pulling which is

00:24:52.559 --> 00:24:57.679
basically to average out all of this uh

00:24:54.960 --> 00:25:00.400
evidence that it finds this detective

00:24:57.679 --> 00:25:03.919
that we have and at the end it gives us

00:25:00.400 --> 00:25:07.279
a smooth more general summary of those

00:25:03.919 --> 00:25:10.799
features that it finds. So usually you

00:25:07.279 --> 00:25:13.760
will see that we go with max pooling uh

00:25:10.799 --> 00:25:15.679
because of this sharper aggregation that

00:25:13.760 --> 00:25:17.520
it has.

00:25:15.679 --> 00:25:20.320
But of course all of these uh both of

00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:23.039
these methods are uh providing this

00:25:20.320 --> 00:25:27.279
translation invariance that is the key

00:25:23.039 --> 00:25:29.600
for us for the image data. So uh we are

00:25:27.279 --> 00:25:33.600
going to use all of uh this uh

00:25:29.600 --> 00:25:38.559
principles and these tools in building

00:25:33.600 --> 00:25:41.919
our CNNs. Well, uh we will review the uh

00:25:38.559 --> 00:25:45.200
history of this CNN architectures and

00:25:41.919 --> 00:25:50.880
the reason is as you saw basically C

00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:54.080
what CNN does is uh it starts from some

00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:57.200
early layers that learns uh features

00:25:54.080 --> 00:26:00.320
that can be generic and

00:25:57.200 --> 00:26:03.520
um with the intermediate layer we will

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:05.279
aggregate this generic features to build

00:26:03.520 --> 00:26:08.159
up larger

00:26:05.279 --> 00:26:12.640
parts of the images for example

00:26:08.159 --> 00:26:17.039
textures, patterns, uh eyes, wheels and

00:26:12.640 --> 00:26:21.360
leaves. So you may ask yourself well can

00:26:17.039 --> 00:26:25.440
I uh use this uh features that I learn

00:26:21.360 --> 00:26:29.600
from some other network even uh in my

00:26:25.440 --> 00:26:33.360
own network without training those uh

00:26:29.600 --> 00:26:36.720
early layers for the task that I'm

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:40.000
interested in. So for instance, if we

00:26:36.720 --> 00:26:43.440
have a network that is trained on a very

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:45.760
very large data set which requires uh a

00:26:43.440 --> 00:26:48.559
lot of training and a lot of resources,

00:26:45.760 --> 00:26:51.440
for example, a data set like imageet

00:26:48.559 --> 00:26:55.200
that has a thousand classes like dog,

00:26:51.440 --> 00:26:59.279
car, chair and so on and so forth. uh

00:26:55.200 --> 00:27:02.640
the ability of this CNN to basically

00:26:59.279 --> 00:27:06.480
detect edges, textures, shapes and

00:27:02.640 --> 00:27:09.279
eventually objects can be reused in

00:27:06.480 --> 00:27:12.000
another neural network and we basically

00:27:09.279 --> 00:27:15.279
we can freeze that though that that

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:19.200
early layers and we don't need to really

00:27:15.279 --> 00:27:22.960
train that part and then add more layer

00:27:19.200 --> 00:27:25.360
after that to process these features in

00:27:22.960 --> 00:27:28.240
a way that we want for the specific task

00:27:25.360 --> 00:27:32.559
that we are interested in. So this is

00:27:28.240 --> 00:27:34.159
known as transfer learning that uh

00:27:32.559 --> 00:27:37.679
justifies

00:27:34.159 --> 00:27:40.720
training a very very good architectures

00:27:37.679 --> 00:27:44.400
as some sort of pre-trained network that

00:27:40.720 --> 00:27:48.880
can be used elsewhere. So usually what

00:27:44.400 --> 00:27:52.480
we do is we uh split the model uh the

00:27:48.880 --> 00:27:55.200
CNN model in two parts. One is the

00:27:52.480 --> 00:27:58.000
convolutional base which is basically

00:27:55.200 --> 00:28:00.720
this early layers that we discussed that

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:02.880
uh they do the feature extraction and

00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:05.520
then we have an we have a head at the

00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:10.000
end that aggregate the this final

00:28:05.520 --> 00:28:14.399
aggregated uh features that uh basically

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:16.480
use them. It can be even a linear MLP

00:28:14.399 --> 00:28:19.039
that uses these features just like a

00:28:16.480 --> 00:28:21.919
regression that uses the feature and

00:28:19.039 --> 00:28:25.760
make a decision on for example if this

00:28:21.919 --> 00:28:28.320
is a cat or dog uh while we are using

00:28:25.760 --> 00:28:31.279
this convolutional base that can do much

00:28:28.320 --> 00:28:32.720
more than just detecting cat and dog.

00:28:31.279 --> 00:28:35.200
But for some reason you're only

00:28:32.720 --> 00:28:37.360
interested in this final task and you

00:28:35.200 --> 00:28:39.679
can use this overengineered

00:28:37.360 --> 00:28:43.840
convolutional base that can give you

00:28:39.679 --> 00:28:46.320
your cat and dog detection uh with very

00:28:43.840 --> 00:28:48.320
high confidence while you haven't really

00:28:46.320 --> 00:28:51.520
done any of that training and somebody

00:28:48.320 --> 00:28:55.200
else did it with a very ad advanced

00:28:51.520 --> 00:28:58.080
state-ofthe-art CNN base. So it's enough

00:28:55.200 --> 00:29:01.200
to just replace the head and with a few

00:28:58.080 --> 00:29:04.799
shot training in your own data set for

00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:07.279
example you can train that part this

00:29:04.799 --> 00:29:10.320
classification head while you're not

00:29:07.279 --> 00:29:12.559
touching the the base. This basically

00:29:10.320 --> 00:29:16.320
justifies training very good

00:29:12.559 --> 00:29:20.080
convolutional bases. And uh we will talk

00:29:16.320 --> 00:29:24.320
about some famous uh convolutional bases

00:29:20.080 --> 00:29:28.640
that we can use uh in our own tasks and

00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:31.039
we can just basically take them and

00:29:28.640 --> 00:29:34.000
uh without training. We just need to

00:29:31.039 --> 00:29:36.399
train some classification head at the

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:39.919
end and that doesn't really require a

00:29:36.399 --> 00:29:39.919
lot of training and a lot of data.
